Matthis stepped inside the Oak and Ember and dripped next to the door. The air was moist but warm. The fire spat in the giant hearth. The place was packed. He heard loud guffaws from one table that sounded like donkey brays. The men and women nearby seemed to be poking fun at the strange laughter. 

"When I says yer an ass, I didn't think you'd become one!"

The braying guffaw was almost downed out by cries of surprise from a group gathered around a deck of playing cards.

"Luckiest hand I've seen, that was."

"You cheat. I can't believe you won again."

"I don't cheat. I'm just smarter than you lot."

One of the players was Rafe. "Been a while since I've lost like that. Care for another hand?"

Matthis scanned the room for red curly hair. He squeezed between the benches and dripped next to the fire. One of the pots threatened to boil over. He glanced toward the kitchen and nudged the crane with the poker. The boil calmed to a simmer. He checked the pile of wood in one corner. Only large pieces left. 

No one but Matthis heard the little squeal from the kitchen over the braying laughter. He slipped his head inside and saw Aura sitting in a pile of flour and holding the bag in front of her. Elspeth's usual hair kerchief was gone and she had to pull back the strands. 

"Aura," she said, her voice strained, "I asked you please don't touch that." Aura's lip quivered. 

Matthis checked the pots on the fire again. They smelled of herbs with chicken and vegetables. His hand hesitated by the ladle that hung from the mantle. He pulled his hand away. Instead, he squeezed between the benches again and plunged outside. 

He rounded the building to the back. A pile of round blocks stood against the wall. A sloped roof shielded them from the rain. An axe hung from a nail. He set about splitting the blocks. 

The rain made the haft a little slippery. But he adjusted his grip and fell into a rhythm. Set, swing, gather. Before long, he had a neat hearth-ready pile. He bent and lifted a few. 

"What are you doing."

Elspeth stood at the corner of the house, her hair frizzled around her head. Her hand was on her heart. Her cheeks were white. "Why are you chopping logs, Matthis."

Arms full of wood, Matthis faced her. Her eyes were a brighter green than usual. Water streamed down her face. Her lips were red. Her eyes didn't leave his as he stepped forward and stood next to her. 

"I didn't want you to do it alone."

They stood there in the rain. One of her hands gripped the hem of her apron. She held the other over her heart. 

"I thought you were Father," she said.

The rain eased to a patter. Matthis didn't look away. Neither did she. 

"It's been years, Matthis." Her voice broke. "Years and years."

Matthis shifted the wood. He touched her cheek. Her hand lifted to his. Her mouth opened a little, and her eyes widened.

"He's at peace," said Matthis. "But you're not alone. Elspeth." He felt her shiver. "You're not alone."

He nodded and began to pull away. She touched his arm. He stopped and faced her again. They stood there for a moment. His fingers rested on her cheek. She squeezed his hand. Not all the water on her face was rain. 

Matthis smiled. Elspeth gasped and reached up. She hesitated and almost pulled her hand away. She searched his eyes and then slowly, gently extended her fingers and touched his lips. She whispered. 

"How long has it been since I've seen you smile?"

Matthis stroked her cheek and said nothing. 

--